<span id="freeTextContainer11653247064287554650"><b>”It was not a miracle. Bestowed by God. Offered by a human. I stayed on my knees. In the dust where my heart will remain each night and every day until you understand what I know and long to tell you: to be given dominion over another is a hard thing; to wrest dominion over another is a wrong thing; to give dominion of yourself to another is a wicked thing.”</b><br/><br/><i>A Mercy</i> is perhaps my favorite Toni Morrison novel. Morrison never compromises her story-tellng for the reader, and Morrison’s fiction somet</span>
  <span id="freeText11653247064287554650" style="display:none"><b>”It was not a miracle. Bestowed by God. Offered by a human. I stayed on my knees. In the dust where my heart will remain each night and every day until you understand what I know and long to tell you: to be given dominion over another is a hard thing; to wrest dominion over another is a wrong thing; to give dominion of yourself to another is a wicked thing.”</b><br /><br /><i>A Mercy</i> is perhaps my favorite Toni Morrison novel. Morrison never compromises her story-tellng for the reader, and Morrison’s fiction sometimes proves difficult for me to follow. But <i>A Mercy</i> is brief, engrossing, and features Morrison’s gorgeous prose: it encourages and rewards rereading. <i>A Mercy</i> is among a handful or two of modern classics novels about America’s frontiers. 4.5 stars<br /></span>
