<div id="review_2398828743" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2398828743" />
    <a title="La Tonya  Jordan" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/32053623-la-tonya-jordan"><img alt="La Tonya  Jordan" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1501465115p2/32053623.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2398828743?book_show_action=true">Nov 04, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="La Tonya  Jordan" class="user" itemprop="url" name="La Tonya  Jordan" href="/user/show/32053623-la-tonya-jordan">La Tonya  Jordan</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>


          <div><span class="uitext greyText">Recommends it for: </span>
           <span class="uitext reviewText">Everyone</span></div>

          <div>
    <span class="greyText">Recommended to La Tonya  by: </span>
      Myself 
  </div>


          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/32053623-la-tonya-jordan?shelf=favorites">favorites</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2398828743" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17034474769631156225">What can I say about this marvelous read, the poetry of the language is music to my ears. I can feel the anguish of those owned and indentured to others. The desire for love and family no matter how it comes to you. The agony of wanting freedom others have or what others appear to have in their possession. Desperately wanting to hold onto memories of Africa, villages, land, and customs ripped from you. Distressed over circumstances you cannot control. <br/><br/>This is a story of a young girl named Floren</span>
  <span id="freeText17034474769631156225" style="display:none">What can I say about this marvelous read, the poetry of the language is music to my ears. I can feel the anguish of those owned and indentured to others. The desire for love and family no matter how it comes to you. The agony of wanting freedom others have or what others appear to have in their possession. Desperately wanting to hold onto memories of Africa, villages, land, and customs ripped from you. Distressed over circumstances you cannot control. <br /><br />This is a story of a young girl named Florens who was traded to Jacob Vaark, an Anglo-Dutch trader, to settle a debt from a plantation owner. Florens mother, a prize slave, offered her to Vaark. He takes her far away north from her home where she meets Lina, Sorrow, and Mistress, Rebekka, Vaark's wife. She does find warmth and friendship among this household. She believes she has found a home until Vaark dies and circumstances changes like the weather and the wind. Read to find out the secrets not shared. The resentments held deep within the soul. Hear the cries for help no one sees......... A beautiful read. <br /><br />Quote: <br /><br />Fined five thousand pounds of tobacco by the Lord Proprietarys' magistrate for throwing their bodies too close to the bay; forced to scoop up the corpes-those they could find (they used pikes and nets, D'Ortega said, a purchase which itself cost two pounds, six)---and ordered to burn or bury them. <br /><br />That God hated idleness most of all, so staring off into space to weep for a mother or a playmate was to court damnation. <br /><br />When Lina tried to enlighten her, saying, "You are one leaf on his tree," Florens shook her head, closed her eyes and replied, "No. I am his tree." <br /><br />It is one matter to live in your own waste; it is another to live in another's.</span>
  <a data-text-id="17034474769631156225" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

